    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Lead routing</strong> is the process of automatically assigning each incoming lead to the sales representative best positioned to close them — based on rules like territory, company size, industry, or lead score. Without it, leads land in a shared queue where response speed is random and rep-to-lead fit is left to chance. Good routing makes the right person responsible from minute one.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Response time impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">7x faster qualification</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary benefit</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Rep-to-lead fit</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Speed-to-lead is one of the most consistent predictors of whether an inbound prospect becomes a customer. Harvard Business Review research found that contacting a lead within 1 hour makes you 7x more likely to qualify them than responding after just one hour. Lead routing is the infrastructure that makes fast, correct response automatic rather than accidental.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is lead routing?</h2>
        <p>Lead routing (also called lead assignment or lead distribution) is a set of rules — configured in your CRM or marketing automation platform — that determine which sales rep receives ownership of a new lead the moment it enters your system.</p>
        <p>In a small team with one or two reps, this is trivial. In a team with dozens of reps across regions, product lines, and deal sizes, routing determines whether a $200,000 enterprise lead lands with your most experienced account executive or sits unread in a shared inbox until someone notices.</p>
        <p>Common routing criteria include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Geography</strong> — route by country, state, or postal code to match reps who cover that territory</li>
          <li><strong>Company size</strong> — SMB leads to inside sales, enterprise leads to named account executives</li>
          <li><strong>Industry or vertical</strong> — route healthcare leads to reps who know HIPAA, fintech leads to those who understand compliance</li>
          <li><strong>Lead score</strong> — high-scoring leads go immediately to senior reps; low-scoring leads enter a nurture sequence</li>
          <li><strong>Product interest</strong> — leads enquiring about Product A route to the Product A specialist team</li>
          <li><strong>Round-robin</strong> — distribute evenly across available reps when no other criteria apply</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Speed-to-lead data</div>
          <p>A Harvard Business Review study of 2,241 US companies found that firms that tried to contact leads <strong>within 1 hour</strong> were 7x more likely to qualify them than those who waited even 1 hour, and 60x more likely to qualify them than companies that waited 24 hours. Routing is how you engineer that response time at scale.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why lead routing matters for revenue teams</h2>
        <p>Most revenue teams that skip routing assume the problem is lead volume or sales skill. Often it is neither — it is leads sitting in the wrong hands or in no hands at all. Three mechanisms explain routing's revenue impact:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Response time.</strong> Automated routing means no manual triage step. The moment a form is submitted, a rep is notified. Without routing, someone has to read a shared inbox, decide who should own it, and forward it — a process that adds hours to response time in high-volume environments.</li>
          <li><strong>Rep expertise match.</strong> A rep who closes manufacturing deals every day will outperform a generalist on a manufacturing lead, even if the generalist has more experience overall. Routing by vertical or use case puts the best-fit rep on each opportunity.</li>
          <li><strong>Accountability.</strong> When a lead has a named owner from the moment it arrives, there is no ambiguity. Revenue operations can track response time, follow-up cadence, and close rate by rep and by lead source — and fix gaps with data.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How lead routing works</h2>
        <p>Routing operates as a rules engine. When a lead enters the system — via form submission, chat, inbound call, or import — the engine evaluates the lead's attributes against a priority-ordered set of rules and assigns it accordingly.</p>

        <h3>Rules-based routing</h3>
        <p>The most common implementation. You define conditions: "If company size is over 500 employees AND industry is healthcare, assign to the Enterprise Healthcare team." Rules cascade in priority order — the first matching rule wins. Most CRMs (HubSpot, Salesforce) implement this natively.</p>

        <h3>Round-robin routing</h3>
        <p>Leads are distributed evenly across a pool of reps — rep 1 gets lead 1, rep 2 gets lead 2, and so on. Used when leads are relatively uniform in size and no rep specialisation applies. The risk is that one absent rep accumulates unworked leads during a round-robin cycle.</p>

        <h3>Score-based routing</h3>
        <p>Combines lead scoring with routing: high-score leads (70+) route immediately to senior reps with an SLA for response within 15 minutes. Mid-score leads (40-69) enter a nurture sequence. Low-score leads (under 40) receive automated email until they score higher or opt out. This tiering prevents junior reps from spending time on unqualified prospects.</p>

        <h3>Availability-based routing</h3>
        <p>Routes to reps who are currently logged in or within business hours. Common in chat and phone contexts. Prevents leads from being assigned to reps on holiday or in a different timezone who won't see the notification for eight hours.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Lead routing methods compared</h2>

