        <h2 id="examples">Real lead routing examples</h2>
        <p>The theory is simple. The execution varies significantly by team size and go-to-market motion. Three patterns that illustrate the range.</p>

        <h3>1. Local fitness studio</h3>
        <p>A franchise with five locations ran Facebook ads targeting people within 5 miles of each gym. Routing assigned each form submission to the studio manager of the nearest location, who responded within 30 minutes with a personalised trial offer. Cost per acquired member dropped 40% over three months versus the previous approach of routing all leads to one central desk.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B SaaS — enterprise vs SMB split</h3>
        <p>A CRM company used company size (pulled from Clearbit enrichment) as the primary routing criterion. Companies over 200 employees routed to an enterprise team with a 1-hour SLA. Companies under 200 employees went to inside sales with a self-serve onboarding sequence. The enterprise team's close rate improved 28% after they stopped competing with SMB volume for attention.</p>

        <h3>3. Agency with vertical specialists</h3>
        <p>A digital marketing agency created routing rules by industry: retail leads went to the retail team, healthcare leads to the healthcare team, and so on. Reps led with industry-specific case studies and spoke the client's compliance language from first contact. Average sales cycle dropped from 45 days to 29 days.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Lead routing vs lead scoring — how they work together</h2>
        <p>Lead scoring and lead routing solve adjacent problems and are most powerful in combination.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Lead scoring</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Answers: is this lead worth pursuing?</li>
              <li>Assigns a numerical value (0-100) to each lead</li>
              <li>Based on fit criteria and engagement signals</li>
              <li>Determines when a lead is ready for sales</li>
              <li>Output: MQL threshold, SQL threshold</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Lead routing</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Answers: who should pursue this lead?</li>
              <li>Assigns the lead to a specific rep or queue</li>
              <li>Based on territory, size, vertical, score</li>
              <li>Determines which rep contacts the lead</li>
              <li>Output: assigned owner, SLA timer starts</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 lead routing best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start simple and add rules incrementally.</strong> Two or three routing criteria — territory and company size — cover the majority of routing needs. Add vertical, product interest, and score-based tiers once the foundation is working.</li>
          <li><strong>Set SLA by lead tier.</strong> Not all leads warrant the same response time. Enterprise, high-score inbound leads might carry a 15-minute SLA; mid-tier leads might carry a 4-hour window. Make the SLA visible in your CRM and alert managers when it is missed.</li>
          <li><strong>Enrich leads before routing.</strong> Routing on job title or company size is only accurate if that data exists. Tools like Clearbit or Apollo can enrich form submissions with firmographic data before the routing rule fires, improving match accuracy.</li>
          <li><strong>Handle unmatched leads explicitly.</strong> Every routing setup needs a fallback — a queue or rep who receives leads that don't match any rule. Without a fallback, leads fall through gaps silently.</li>
          <li><strong>Review routing rules quarterly.</strong> Sales territories change, reps leave, product lines split. Routing rules built in Q1 are often broken by Q3. Schedule a quarterly audit of rule logic and rep capacity.</li>
          <li><strong>Measure response time and close rate by route.</strong> The purpose of routing is better outcomes. Track time-to-first-contact and close rate by routing rule to identify which assignments actually improve results.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — routing without a fallback</div>
          <p>Most routing configurations handle the common cases and leave edge cases unspecified. If a lead doesn't match any rule, it either goes nowhere or lands in a generic inbox nobody monitors. Define an explicit fallback owner or queue — this single step prevents the most costly lead leakage.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common lead routing mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No fallback rule.</strong> Leads that match nothing land nowhere. Always define a catch-all queue or rep.</li>
          <li><strong>Routing by rep availability without accounting for off-hours.</strong> A live chat routed to a rep who clocked out at 5 PM generates a notification nobody sees until morning.</li>
          <li><strong>Stale territory assignments.</strong> Reps leave, territories shift. An annual review of routing logic is not enough — build a quarterly check into RevOps cadence.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-engineering the rules too early.</strong> Ten routing conditions applied before you have data on what actually matters creates a brittle, unmaintainable system. Start with two rules and iterate.</li>
          <li><strong>Routing without enrichment.</strong> Routing on company size is meaningless if most form submissions don't include company size. Use enrichment to fill the data gaps before routing fires.</li>
        </ul>

